Found it — pretty sure. In `turbo.json`:

```json
{
  "pipeline": {
    "build": { "dependsOn": ["^build", "images:optimize"], "outputs": [".next/**"] },
    "images:optimize": { "outputs": [".next/cache/images/**"] }
  }
}
```

Both `build` and `images:optimize` declare overlapping outputs under `.next/`. Turbo runs them in parallel because `images:optimize` doesn't `dependsOn` build. When the image optimizer is mid-write to `.next/cache/images/*` and the Next build also touches `.next/cache/*` (e.g., the webpack cache restoration), you get EBUSY on the cache directory.

The 1-in-4 frequency matches a race condition: it depends on which task finishes hashing first. Let me verify by checking the failing deploy logs.
